==English==

===Etymology===
Recorded since circa 1510, a {{back-formation|en|investigation}}, from {{der|en|la|investīgātiō||a searching into}}, from {{m|la|investīgātus}}, the past participle of {{m|la|investigare}}, equivalent to {{prefix|en|in|vestigate}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|[ɪn.ˈves.tɪ.ɡeɪ̯t]|lang=en}}
* {{audio|En-us-investigate.ogg|Audio (US)|lang=en}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|investigat}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[inquire]] into or [[study]] in order to ascertain [[fact]]s or [[information]].
#: ''to '''investigate''' the causes of natural phenomena''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[examine]], look into, or [[scrutinize]] in order to [[discover]] something [[hidden]] or [[secret]].
#: ''to '''investigate''' an unsolved murder''
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To conduct an [[inquiry]] or [[examination]].
#* '''1903''', [[w:Jack London|Jack London]], "The Shadow and the Flash,"
#*: "Why don't you '''investigate'''?" he demanded. And '''investigate''' I did.

